From: Claude (devcontainer agent)
Date: 2026-04-27
Subject: [I5] Followup: state-file gate for setup_plugin_marketplaces

Why this is a separate patch
============================
This devcontainer mounts /workspace/.devcontainer as read-only inside
the container, so an agent running inside cannot edit Dockerfile or
post_install.py directly. Apply this patch from the host (or any
environment with write access to .devcontainer/), then commit and push.

Order of application: this patch operates on the post_install.py STATE
that results from applying both `2026-04-27-post_install-correctness-
and-hardening.patch` and `2026-04-27-marketplace-runtime-add.patch`
(it modifies the setup_plugin_marketplaces function introduced by the
latter). Apply order:

  1. paad/code-reviews/deferred/2026-04-27-post_install-correctness-and-hardening.patch
  2. paad/code-reviews/deferred/2026-04-27-marketplace-runtime-add.patch
  3. paad/code-reviews/deferred/2026-04-27-fix_directory_ownership-symlink-args-walk.patch
  4. paad/code-reviews/deferred/2026-04-27-post_install-correctness-followup.patch
  5. paad/code-reviews/deferred/2026-04-27-marketplace-state-file-followup.patch  (this one)

What this fixes (review item I5 — review 2026-04-27 18:27)
==========================================================

I5 (Important): marketplace runtime-add widens TOFU window
----------------------------------------------------------
The parent (`2026-04-27-marketplace-runtime-add.patch`) correctly
moves the three `claude plugin marketplace add` calls from the
Dockerfile build step (where they were shadowed by the named-volume
mount on /home/vscode/.claude after first creation) to
postCreateCommand, where they apply on every container creation.

Trust-frequency consequence: pre-parent, the marketplace manifests
were re-fetched once per image rebuild (rare — Renovate-driven).
Post-parent, they re-fetch on every "Reopen in Container", every fresh
clone, every devcontainer recreate — frequent, daily. With
bypassPermissions opt-in, NET_ADMIN/NET_RAW caps, and the R/W
workspace mount, plugin compromise has wide blast radius (already
tracked in backlog `2b9f7d63` as the static "unpinned" concern). The
frequency-of-trust-event is a separate axis the parent does not
address — its trust-posture commentary was carried forward verbatim.

An attacker who briefly compromises a third-party marketplace upstream
(e.g. `trailofbits/skills`) lands plugin code on the next container
creation, not the next image build. Window expands from "weeks" to
"minutes/hours."

Fix: hash the canonical marketplace list and persist it to a state
file at `~/.claude/.smudge-marketplaces-registered`. On subsequent
runs, skip the `claude plugin marketplace add` calls if the prior hash
matches the current list. The named volume persists state across
recreations, so closing the per-creation re-fetch loop does not
reintroduce the original volume-shadowing bug.

Refresh paths:
  - Delete the state file (`rm
    ~/.claude/.smudge-marketplaces-registered`) to force re-registration
    on the next container creation.
  - Change the marketplaces list (add/remove an entry); the new hash
    will mismatch the stored hash and trigger re-registration.
  - Failed registrations skip the state-file write so the next run
    retries against upstream.

The hash is over the SORTED list (so list-order changes don't
gratuitously re-register) and uses SHA-256 (overkill for an integrity
check, but readily available via stdlib hashlib).

How to apply
============
From a shell on the host (NOT inside the devcontainer):

  cd <smudge repo root>
  # Apply the prior 4 patches first (see Order of application)
  git apply paad/code-reviews/deferred/2026-04-27-marketplace-state-file-followup.patch
  git add .devcontainer/post_install.py
  git commit -m "fix(devcontainer): state-file gate for marketplace registration (I5)"

Then push.

